					<canvas id="transferChart"></canvas>
				</div>
			</div>

			<h2 id="which-platform-should-you-choose">Which platform should you choose?</h2>
			<div class="choose-grid">
				<div class="ch-col study">
					<div class="ch-head">Choose Study.com if…</div>
					<ul>
						<li>You need upper-division or advanced credits</li>
						<li>You want the broadest catalog (220+ courses)</li>
						<li>You want ACE and NCCRS recommendations</li>
						<li>You prefer open-book, non-proctored exams</li>
						<li>You want a flat plan with the lowest entry price</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
				<div class="ch-col sophia">
					<div class="ch-head">Choose Sophia if…</div>
					<ul>
						<li>You want the cheapest fast path through gen-eds</li>
						<li>You can complete several courses in one month</li>
						<li>You prefer fully self-paced, assessment-based study</li>
						<li>You mostly need lower-division requirements</li>
						<li>Your target school already recognizes Sophia credits</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
				<div class="ch-col straight">
					<div class="ch-head">Choose StraighterLine if…</div>
					<ul>
						<li>Your school has a direct StraighterLine pathway</li>
						<li>You want 24/7 tutoring and academic advising</li>
						<li>You need one or two very specific courses</li>
						<li>You prefer structured assignments and finals</li>
						<li>Transfer certainty is your top priority</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
			</div>

			<h2 id="smart-enrollment-workflow">Smart enrollment workflow</h2>
			<p>
				For transfer-friendly schools such as WGU, SNHU, Purdue Global, UMPI, Excelsior, TESU, and Charter Oak, follow
				this process before spending any money.
			</p>
			<div class="workflow">
				<div class="wf-step">
					<div class="wf-num s1">1</div>
					<div class="wf-text">
						<strong>Identify the exact course requirement</strong> — get the specific course name and number from your
						degree plan or academic advisor.
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="wf-step">
					<div class="wf-num s2">2</div>
					<div class="wf-text">
						<strong>Check your school's equivalency list</strong> — most transfer-friendly schools publish
						course-by-course equivalency tables for each platform.
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="wf-step">
					<div class="wf-num s3">3</div>
					<div class="wf-text">
						<strong>Compare total cost across all three</strong> — use the calculator above. The cheapest platform per
						credit varies by how many courses you take.
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="wf-step">
					<div class="wf-num s4">4</div>
					<div class="wf-text">
						<strong>Enroll only after transfer confirmation</strong> — get written confirmation from your registrar
						before spending money on any alternative credit course.
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="divider"></div>

			<h2 id="frequently-asked-questions">Frequently asked questions</h2>
			<div class="faq-block">
				<details class="faq-item">
					<summary class="faq-q">What is the difference between Study.com, Sophia Learning, and StraighterLine?</summary>
					<div class="faq-a">
						Study.com has the broadest catalog with upper-division options and dual ACE + NCCRS recommendations.
						Sophia is the cheapest flat-rate option for bulk general education completion. StraighterLine has the
						largest direct partner-school network and the most structured course support.
					</div>
				</details>
				<details class="faq-item">
					<summary class="faq-q">Which platform is cheapest?</summary>
					<div class="faq-a">
						Study.com starts lowest at $95/month. Sophia is $99/month flat with all courses included. StraighterLine
						is typically the most expensive for multiple courses because it charges $79 per course on top of the $99
						membership fee.
					</div>
				</details>
				<details class="faq-item">
					<summary class="faq-q">Which platform transfers best?</summary>
					<div class="faq-a">
						StraighterLine has the largest direct partner network (180+ schools), but transfer approval always depends
						on the receiving college's own policies. All three platforms use ACE credit recommendations as the
						baseline.
					</div>
				</details>
				<details class="faq-item">
					<summary class="faq-q">Which is best for general education credits?</summary>
					<div class="faq-a">
						Sophia is usually best for gen-ed credits because of its low flat-rate cost and self-paced format. Taking
						three or more courses in a single month makes it significantly cheaper than the other two platforms.
					</div>
				</details>
				<details class="faq-item">
					<summary class="faq-q">Which is best for upper-division credits?</summary>
					<div class="faq-a">
						Study.com is the only platform of the three that offers upper-division alternative credit courses. Sophia
						and StraighterLine focus almost entirely on lower-division general education.
					</div>
				</details>
				<details class="faq-item">
					<summary class="faq-q">Can these credits transfer to a university?</summary>
					<div class="faq-a">
						Yes, but transfer is never automatic. The receiving university decides whether a course counts and how it
						applies to the degree plan. Always verify equivalency before enrolling.
					</div>
				</details>
				<details class="faq-item">
					<summary class="faq-q">Is Sophia easier than Study.com?</summary>
					<div class="faq-a">
						Generally yes. Sophia is more streamlined and assessment-focused. Study.com includes more video lessons,
						quizzes, and structured content before the final exam.
					</div>
				</details>
				<details class="faq-item">
					<summary class="faq-q">Is StraighterLine better than Sophia?</summary>
					<div class="faq-a">
						StraighterLine can be better if a student wants stronger support, a more traditional course format, or a
						direct pathway to a specific school. For pure cost efficiency across multiple courses, Sophia usually
						wins.
					</div>
				</details>
				<details class="faq-item">
					<summary class="faq-q">Which platform is best overall?</summary>
					<div class="faq-a">
						Study.com is the strongest all-around option, Sophia is the best budget option, and StraighterLine is the
						best partnership-first option.
					</div>
				</details>
			</div>

			<h2 id="people-also-ask">People also ask</h2>
			<div class="paa-block" id="paa-block">
				<div class="paa-item">
					<button type="button" class="paa-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="paa-ans-0" id="paa-q-0">
						Are Study.com, Sophia Learning, and StraighterLine accredited?
						<span class="paa-icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
					</button>
					<div class="paa-a" hidden id="paa-ans-0" role="region" aria-labelledby="paa-q-0">
						<p>
							None of the three platforms are accredited institutions — accreditation is reserved for degree-granting
							colleges and universities. What they do carry are ACE (American Council on Education) credit recommendations,
							which is the same external framework many schools use to evaluate military transcripts and corporate
							training. Study.com additionally carries NCCRS recommendations, giving it a second recognized standard.
							When credits transfer to your college, they appear on your official transcript as regular college credits
							— employers see your degree, not the platform you used.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="paa-item">
					<button type="button" class="paa-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="paa-ans-1" id="paa-q-1">
						How fast can you complete a course on each platform?
						<span class="paa-icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
					</button>
					<div class="paa-a" hidden id="paa-ans-1" role="region" aria-labelledby="paa-q-1">
						<p>
							Speed varies significantly by platform and student effort. On Sophia, motivated students can finish a
							straightforward gen-ed course in 3–7 days working several hours daily, though courses with multiple
							Touchstone essays take longer — Touchstones are manually graded and can take up to 7 business days to
							return. Study.com courses typically take 1–3 weeks depending on the subject and how many video lessons
							are involved; final exam results are instant since exams are open-book and auto-graded. StraighterLine
							courses can be completed in 5–7 days for most general education subjects, or 7–14 days for science,
							English, healthcare, and writing-heavy courses. As of September 2025, StraighterLine no longer requires
							live proctoring on any of its courses. The practical speed ceiling across all three platforms is roughly
							3–5 courses per month for a full-time student.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="paa-item">
					<button type="button" class="paa-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="paa-ans-2" id="paa-q-2">
						Does Study.com have proctored exams?
						<span class="paa-icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
					</button>
					<div class="paa-a" hidden id="paa-ans-2" role="region" aria-labelledby="paa-q-2">
						<p>
							Study.com College Saver uses open-book, non-proctored final exams that are auto-graded instantly at
							submission — no webcam, no scheduling, no HonorLock required. Sophia also uses unproctored exams, though
							some courses include Touchstone assignments that require written essays graded manually by a reviewer.
							StraighterLine removed its HonorLock proctoring requirement in September 2025 and no longer requires live
							proctoring on any course. All three platforms are now fully non-proctored for standard assessments, which
							is a major shift from prior years.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="paa-item">
					<button type="button" class="paa-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="paa-ans-3" id="paa-q-3">
						Which platform is best for WGU, SNHU, or Purdue Global?
						<span class="paa-icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
					</button>
					<div class="paa-a" hidden id="paa-ans-3" role="region" aria-labelledby="paa-q-3">
						<p>
							All three platforms publish transfer guides for WGU, SNHU, Purdue Global, TESU, and other
							transfer-friendly schools, but the best choice still depends on the specific course. For WGU, Sophia tends
							to be the most popular starting point for bulk gen-ed credits because of its flat-rate pricing and wide WGU
							equivalency list. Study.com is often preferred for upper-division or more specialized courses that WGU
							requires. For SNHU, StraighterLine has a direct partnership that makes transfer more predictable. The
							safest approach for any school is to check that school's published course equivalency table for each
							platform before enrolling, since WGU's transfer policy was also significantly updated as of February 2026.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="paa-item">
					<button type="button" class="paa-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="paa-ans-4" id="paa-q-4">
						How much can you actually save using these platforms versus a traditional college?
						<span class="paa-icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
					</button>
					<div class="paa-a" hidden id="paa-ans-4" role="region" aria-labelledby="paa-q-4">
						<p>
							The savings are substantial. The average public four-year university charges roughly $1,200 per course. A
							single StraighterLine course costs $178 total (membership + course fee). Sophia costs $99 per month with
							unlimited courses included. Study.com College Saver is $95 per month. A student who completes five general
							education courses in a single month on Sophia spends $99 total — compared to $6,000 or more at a
							traditional university for the same credits. Students who stack multiple courses per billing cycle on
							Study.com or Sophia can realistically save $10,000–$20,000 or more on their total degree cost, depending on
							how many credits transfer and the tuition rate at their receiving school.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="paa-item">
					<button type="button" class="paa-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="paa-ans-5" id="paa-q-5">
						What happens if your school doesn't accept credits from these platforms?
						<span class="paa-icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
					</button>
					<div class="paa-a" hidden id="paa-ans-5" role="region" aria-labelledby="paa-q-5">
						<p>
							If a school does not accept a specific course, the credit does not transfer and you cannot get a refund
							from the platform. This is the most important risk to understand before enrolling. Some schools publish
							blanket policies accepting all ACE-recommended courses; others evaluate each course individually; others
							refuse alternative credit sources entirely. Nursing programs and medical schools are particularly strict —
							most require science prerequisites to come from regionally accredited institutions. The safest step is to
							get written confirmation from your registrar or academic advisor that a specific course from a specific
							platform will transfer and apply to your degree before you pay for anything. Verbal confirmation is not
							enough.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="paa-item">
					<button type="button" class="paa-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="paa-ans-6" id="paa-q-6">
						Can you use more than one platform at the same time?
						<span class="paa-icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
					</button>
					<div class="paa-a" hidden id="paa-ans-6" role="region" aria-labelledby="paa-q-6">
						<p>
							Yes, and many students do. A common strategy is to use Sophia for the cheapest gen-ed requirements,
							Study.com for upper-division or more specialized courses, and StraighterLine for any specific course with a
							confirmed direct-transfer match at the target school. Using all three platforms simultaneously is allowed
							— the platforms have no restrictions on concurrent enrollment. The only limit is your school's cap on
							alternative credit hours, which varies by institution. Most transfer-friendly schools like TESU, WGU, and
							Charter Oak have generous or unlimited alternative credit policies, while more traditional universities may
							cap ACE credit at 30 or 60 transferable hours.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="paa-item">
					<button type="button" class="paa-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="paa-ans-7" id="paa-q-7">
						Is Sophia Learning or Study.com easier to pass?
						<span class="paa-icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
					</button>
					<div class="paa-a" hidden id="paa-ans-7" role="region" aria-labelledby="paa-q-7">
						<p>
							Sophia is generally considered the more streamlined of the two. Its interface is more modern, quizzes are
							well integrated, and most courses are pure assessment-based — you move through challenges and milestones
							without long video lessons. The tradeoff is that Sophia's milestone exams are higher-stakes; some courses
							like Statistics see significant failure rates because there are fewer low-weight practice opportunities to
							buffer your grade. Study.com is more video-heavy and structured, which some students find slower but safer
							— frequent small quizzes provide a grade buffer before the final. Both platforms require a minimum passing
							score of around 70%. Study.com released a new mobile app in late 2025 that closes some of the UX gap with
							Sophia.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>

				<div class="paa-item">
					<button type="button" class="paa-q" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="paa-ans-8" id="paa-q-8">
						Do these credits show up on your college transcript?
						<span class="paa-icon" aria-hidden="true"></span>
					</button>
					<div class="paa-a" hidden id="paa-ans-8" role="region" aria-labelledby="paa-q-8">
						<p>
							Once transferred, the credits appear on your official college transcript as standard college credits —
							the source platform is not mentioned. Employers, graduate schools, and other institutions see only your
							college transcript, not the platform you used to earn the credits. All three platforms provide official
							transcript services to send your grades directly to your receiving school. Study.com and StraighterLine both
							offer transcript delivery as part of their standard service. Sophia provides transcripts through Parchment.
							The credits are functionally indistinguishable from credits earned in a traditional classroom once they
							appear on your official record.
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<h2 id="conclusion">Conclusion</h2>
			<div class="verdict-box">
				<p>
					Study.com is the strongest all-around option for students who need breadth, upper-division flexibility, and a
					flat subscription price. Sophia is usually the best value for fast, low-cost general education completion.
					StraighterLine is often the best choice when a direct pathway, structured support, or a more traditional
					course experience matters most.
				</p>
				<p>
					For most learners, the smartest strategy is to start with your school's transfer requirements, then choose the
					platform — not the other way around.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
